    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Email deliverability</strong> is the percentage of your sent emails that actually reach the recipient's inbox, as opposed to landing in spam, being throttled, or bouncing. It is driven by three signals: <strong>authentication (SPF, DKIM, DMARC), sender reputation, and recipient engagement</strong>. Above 85% inbox placement is healthy; top senders reach 95%+.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Healthy rate</div>
            <div class="tms-value">85%+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Email Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Top signal</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Authentication</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Advanced</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every email that lands in spam is revenue you have already paid to generate. Deliverability is the quiet lever that separates 12% open rates from 42% open rates — long before anyone touches the subject line.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is email deliverability?</h2>
        <p>Email deliverability is the measurement of how many of your sent emails reach the inbox versus the spam folder, throttling queues, or bounce logs. It is not the same as <em>delivery rate</em> — an email can be accepted by Gmail's servers (delivered) and still be filtered straight into spam (not delivered to the inbox).</p>
        <p>Three signals drive inbox placement:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Authentication</strong> — SPF, DKIM, and DMARC records prove you are authorised to send from your domain</li>
          <li><strong>Sender reputation</strong> — a score each mailbox provider assigns you based on bounce rate, complaint rate, spam-trap hits, and volume patterns</li>
          <li><strong>Engagement</strong> — opens, clicks, replies, and forwards signal that recipients want your email</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google and Yahoo 2024 rules</div>
          <p>Since February 2024, Gmail and Yahoo require every bulk sender (5,000+ emails/day) to publish valid <strong>SPF, DKIM, AND DMARC</strong>, keep spam complaint rates under <strong>0.3%</strong>, and offer one-click unsubscribe. Miss any of these and Google will start filtering — regardless of content.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why email deliverability matters</h2>
        <p>Deliverability is the multiplier on every other email metric:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Direct revenue impact.</strong> A 1% improvement in inbox placement on a 100k-subscriber list can recover roughly $50k-$200k per year for an ecommerce brand.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding reputation.</strong> Poor deliverability lowers engagement, which lowers sender reputation, which lowers deliverability further. A downward spiral is often invisible for weeks.</li>
          <li><strong>Silent list decay.</strong> Deliverability degrades without obvious warning. Opens simply drift down 1-2% per month while your list "looks" healthy in the ESP dashboard.</li>
          <li><strong>Regulatory pressure.</strong> Gmail, Yahoo, and Microsoft have all tightened bulk-sender requirements since 2024. Ignoring authentication now means immediate spam filtering.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How email deliverability actually works</h2>
        <p>Every email you send passes three checkpoints before reaching an inbox:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Checkpoint 1 — Authentication</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">SPF:</span> Is this IP authorised to send for your domain?<br>
          <span class="uf-label">DKIM:</span> Is the message cryptographically signed by your domain?<br>
          <span class="uf-label">DMARC:</span> Do SPF and DKIM align with the From address?<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Checkpoint 2 — Sender reputation lookup</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">IP reputation:</span> Bounce rate, complaint rate, spam-trap hits<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Domain reputation:</span> Historical engagement across all IPs<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Checkpoint 3 — Engagement prediction</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Recipient signals:</span> Opens · clicks · replies · forwards<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Content signals:</span> Subject, body, links, images<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-status">→ Inbox · Promotions · Spam · Blocked</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Types of email deliverability issues</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Issue</th><th>What it looks like</th><th>Root cause</th><th>Fix time</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Blocklisting</strong></td>
                <td>Sudden delivery-failure spike</td>
                <td>Complaint spike, spam trap, breach</td>
                <td>2-8 weeks</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Throttling</strong></td><td>Delayed delivery, retries</td><td>Volume spike or new IP</td><td>7-14 days warm-up</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Spam folder placement</strong></td><td>Delivered but hidden</td><td>Low engagement or poor content</td><td>4-6 weeks</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Hard bounces</strong></td><td>Permanent failure</td><td>Invalid addresses on list</td><td>Immediate (list clean)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Soft bounces</strong></td><td>Temporary failure</td><td>Full inbox, server issue</td><td>Retries automatically</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Graymail filtering</strong></td><td>Newsletter unread pile</td><td>Low individual engagement</td><td>2-4 weeks re-engagement</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real email deliverability recoveries</h2>
        <p>Three patterns cover the vast majority of deliverability crashes we see in audits.</p>

        <h3>1. Missing authentication — dental group, 3 locations</h3>
        <p>Open rates dropped from 45% to 18% over 4 weeks after they migrated to a new ESP without setting DKIM or DMARC. Recovery: publish DKIM key + p=none DMARC record, wait 6 weeks with gradual volume ramp. Opens returned to 43%.</p>

        <h3>2. Reputation crash — ecommerce, 80k list</h3>
        <p>Daily blasts through Black Friday pushed Gmail Promotions → spam within 10 days. Complaint rate hit 0.8% (2.6× the Google limit). Recovery: 8-week warm-up on a secondary IP, engaged-only segments first, then gradual expansion. Inbox placement climbed from 42% to 91%.</p>

        <h3>3. Bought list disaster — B2B SaaS startup</h3>
        <p>Purchased 15,000 contacts, hit a 22% bounce rate on first send. Triggered spam traps, landed on Spamhaus. Recovery required 3 months of domain migration, list rebuild from scratch, and formal remediation with Spamhaus.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Deliverability vs delivery rate — which one to track?</h2>
        <p>Both matter, but they measure different things and get gamed differently.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Delivery rate</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Emails accepted by receiving servers</li>
              <li>Shown in every ESP dashboard</li>
              <li>Fails only on bounces / blocks</li>
              <li>Typically reads 97-99%</li>
              <li>Says nothing about inbox vs spam</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Deliverability (inbox placement)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Emails that reach the actual inbox</li>
              <li>Requires seed testing to measure</li>
              <li>Fails on spam folder + throttling</li>
              <li>Typically 78-95%</li>
              <li>Directly predicts revenue</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 best practices for email deliverability</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Publish SPF, DKIM, and DMARC.</strong> Non-negotiable since Google/Yahoo 2024 rules. Start DMARC at p=none, review reports for 30 days, then move to p=quarantine.</li>
          <li><strong>Warm up new IPs and domains.</strong> Never send full volume from day one. Start at 500-1000 per day and double every 2-3 days for the first 30 days.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep complaint rate under 0.1%.</strong> Google's public limit is 0.3%, but the best senders stay below 0.1%. Send only to engaged, opted-in subscribers.</li>
          <li><strong>Prune inactive subscribers quarterly.</strong> Anyone who has not opened or clicked in 6 months should be suppressed. Sending to dead addresses tanks engagement.</li>
          <li><strong>Use a subdomain for marketing.</strong> Send transactional from mail.yourdomain.com and marketing from send.yourdomain.com so a marketing reputation issue never blocks password resets.</li>
          <li><strong>Add one-click unsubscribe.</strong> Required by Gmail/Yahoo since 2024. Add the <code>List-Unsubscribe: One-Click</code> header alongside the visible link.</li>
          <li><strong>Segment by engagement.</strong> Send the newest content to your top 30% engaged first. Engagement compounds — good early signals boost placement for the rest of the send.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor Google Postmaster Tools weekly.</strong> Free, direct-from-Gmail data on domain reputation, complaint rate, authentication, and delivery errors.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — sending to a purchased list</div>
          <p>Purchased or scraped lists always contain spam traps. A single Spamhaus listing takes 6-12 weeks to resolve and can require full domain migration. There is no "small purchase" — one hit destroys years of reputation.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common deliverability mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring soft bounces</strong> — soft bounces that repeat become hard bounces. Suppress after 3 consecutive fails.</li>
          <li><strong>Sending image-only emails</strong> — filters treat image-only messages as classic spam. Always include a text-to-image ratio of at least 60:40.</li>
          <li><strong>Reusing an old ESP without warm-up</strong> — dormant IPs behave like new ones. Warm up before big sends.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping seed tests</strong> — the ESP dashboard shows "delivered" for spam-folder emails. Real inbox placement requires seed-list tools.</li>
          <li><strong>Ramping too fast after a reputation dip</strong> — recovery requires patience. Doubling volume too soon restarts the crash.</li>
        </ul>

